    "## H1 Dataset Description\n",
    "\n",
    "The H1 Dataset is the labeling of every gridbox from the newest ISCCP HGG dataset to one of 11 Weather States (WS) derived from the new ISCCP HGG dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "Gridboxes are assigned a label in the following way:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. If all cells of a gridbox are filled with a masked value, then no data was collected for that gridbox and is assigned the value -127.\n",
    "2. If all cells are the value 0 (no clouds in the gridcell), the gridbox is assigned the value 11 for WS 11.\n",
    "3. For all other cases, compute the Euclidiean distance between the gridbox and WS 1-10 -- the gridbox will be assigned to the WS which resulted in the smallest Euclidean distance.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each file of the H1 dataset contains a year's worth of data made up of 12 3D matricies -- one matrix for each month of the year. \n",
    "\n",
    "Also, each file has a copy of WS derived from the ISCCP HGG dataset of shape (10,42). These WS were used in the creation of this data set and are part of it for reference.\n",
    "\n",
    "The dimensions of each 3D matrix are (N,360,180) and come from the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "* Each file from the ISCCP HGG is composed of measurements over a three hour period. There are eight three hour periods in a day, so N = 8 * number of days in the month.\n",
    "* Once converted from Equal-Area to Equal-Angle formatting, the gridboxes in the ISCCP HGG data are 1x1 degrees (hence the '1' in H1). This corresponds to a grid of (360,180) or 360 degrees longitude and 180 degree latitude.\n",
    "\n",
    "The 3D matricies can then be thought of as N maps of shape (360,180) with each value of the map being the WS assignment for a gridbox from the ISCCP HGG dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Reading and Manipulating DH1 Data\n",
    "\n",
    "The H1 files are in netcdf format which are composed of a **description**, **dimensions** and **variables**. \n",
    "\n",
    "1. The **description** is metadata providing a summary of the dataset description given above. \n",
    "2. **Dimensions** are the possible sizes of the dimensions of M dimensional data a netcdf file can have. As described above, data in each file is 3D with the first dimension having a different size depending on the month of data (except for the WS matrix which has it's own shape).\n",
    "3. **Variables** are the actual data. Each **variable** has a label and is used to access the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "Below are cells which give a brief demonstration on how to read and manipulate the H1 data in Python. The demonstration will show how to load a years worth of data and how to filter and manipulate the data to plot a map of a single WS."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Import python packages\n",
    "# Only numpy and netCDF4 are absolutely required for reading and manipulating the H1 dataset\n",
    "import gc\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from netCDF4 import Dataset\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "# Uncomment the line below to have plots display in their own window that pops up outside the notebook\n",
    "#%matplotlib"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The following cell will show how to obtain a single month of data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "<class 'netCDF4._netCDF4.Dataset'>\n",

      "Data is composed of 12 3D arrays of shape (224-248,360,180) which corresponds to (# of 3-hour files in month, Longitude, Latitude). There are 12 arrays, one for each month, and the first dimension of the array varies from 224-248 due to number of days in each month. Maps have been converted to Equal-Angle format such that when plotted each Gridcell is 1x1 degrees.\n",
      "Gridcell values determined by smallest Euclidean Distance calculation between PC-TAU histogram of gridcell and all Weather States (see ws variable for Weather States). Exceptionif a gridcell contains only zeros (no clouds/cloudless), it is labeled Weather State 11\n",
      "Gridcells can have the following values: \n",
      "No data: -127 \n",
      "Weather State: 1-11 \n",
      "\n",
      "    dimensions(sizes): day31(248), day30(240), day29(232), day28(224), longitude(360), latitude(180), n_centroids(10), pctau_bins(42)\n",
      "    variables(dimensions): float64 \u001b[4mws\u001b[0m(n_centroids,pctau_bins), int8 \u001b[4mjanuary\u001b[0m(day31,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mfebruary\u001b[0m(day29,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mmarch\u001b[0m(day31,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mapril\u001b[0m(day30,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mmay\u001b[0m(day31,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mjune\u001b[0m(day30,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mjuly\u001b[0m(day31,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4maugust\u001b[0m(day31,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mseptember\u001b[0m(day30,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4moctober\u001b[0m(day31,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mnovember\u001b[0m(day30,longitude,latitude), int8 \u001b[4mdecember\u001b[0m(day31,longitude,latitude)\n",
      "    groups: \n",
      "\n"
     ]

      "text/plain": [

   "source": [
    "# Open netcdf file and create netcdf object\n",
    "# Change data_path variable to data of interest\n",
    "data_path = './ncdata/2000.nc'\n",
    "data = Dataset(data_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Printing a netcdf object shows the description, dimensions, and variables\n",
    "print(data)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load the actual data for the month of march\n",
    "# Note that in python the slicing array syntax is necessary\n",
    "# to load the data to memory\n",
    "march_data = data['march'][:,:,:]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Now that data is loaded to memory, close netcdf file\n",
    "data.close()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Filter out gridcells with WS 7\n",
    "# Wherever a gridcell is equal to 7, make gridcell 1, otherwise make 0\n",
    "ws = 7\n",
    "ws_march_data = np.where(march_data==ws,1,0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot for single 3-hour period\n",
    "# Two plots, one (360,180) the other rotated counter-clockwise 90 degrees\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=2)\n",
    "axes[0].imshow(ws_march_data[0,:,:])\n",
    "axes[1].imshow(np.rot90(ws_march_data[0,:,:]))\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Create empty list to hold each variable, or 3D data matrix\n",
    "data_list = []\n",
    "\n",
    "# Open the file and create a netcdf object called data\n",
    "# Use the 'with' command to have python automatically handle\n",
    "# file opening and closing\n",
    "with Dataset(data_path) as data:\n",
    "    for var in data.variables:\n",
    "        # Skip over WS histograms\n",
    "        if var != 'ws':\n",
    "            data_list.append(data[var][:,:,:])\n",
    "        \n",
    "# Choose the WS to filter out and create an empty array\n",
    "# to continually add the results of each month to\n",
    "ws = 7\n",
    "year_plot = np.zeros((360,180))\n",
    "for data in data_list:\n",
    "    # Shape of each array will differ due to number of days in each month\n",
    "    # Every array should only have values of -999 or 1-12\n",
    "    print(data.shape, np.unique(data))\n",
    "    wsdata = np.where(data==ws,1,0)\n",
    "    # Add the number of counts each gridcell was assigned to the WS\n",
    "    year_plot += np.sum(wsdata,axis=0)\n",
    "    \n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=2)\n",
    "axes[0].imshow(year_plot)\n",
    "axes[1].imshow(np.rot90(year_plot))\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

    "# Next, load Weather States (WS) and plot\n",
    "# Note that the Weather States in each file are the same\n",
    "with Dataset(data_path) as data:\n",
    "    ws = data['ws'][:,:]\n",
    "    \n",
    "# Due to how raw data was processed, in order to properly\n",
    "# plot WS centroids, they must be reshaped from vector of length (42)\n",
    "# to a small matrix of shape (6,7) then transposed \n",
    "# (the .T after reshape below does the transpose)\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=3)\n",
    "for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flatten()):\n",
    "    # If statement for removing unwanted axes/empty subplots from showing\n",
    "    if i>=10:\n",
    "        ax.set_axis_off()\n",
    "        continue\n",
    "    ax.imshow(ws[i,:].reshape(6,7).T)"
   ]
